  "prompt": "How do you put on fake eyelashes without glue?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, you can't apply traditional strip lashes without some sort of adhesive. However, there are glue-free options that are designed to work differently:\n\n**1. Magnetic Eyelashes:**\n\n*   **How they work:** Magnetic lashes consist of a strip of lashes with tiny magnets along the base. They usually come with two sets of lash strips *per eye*. You sandwich your natural lashes between these two magnetic strips. One strip goes above your natural lash line, and the other goes below. The magnets attract each other, holding the fake lashes in place.\n*   **Application:**\n    1.  **Curl your natural lashes:** This helps them blend better with the falsies.\n    2.  **Apply mascara (optional):** A light coat of mascara can give the magnetic lashes something to grip onto.\n    3.  **Position the top strip:** Hold the top strip of magnetic lashes close to your upper lash line, aligning it with the outer corner of your eye. Position it *above* your natural lashes, as close to the lash line as possible.\n    4.  **Position the bottom strip:** Hold the bottom strip of magnetic lashes *underneath* your upper lash line, directly aligning with the top strip. The magnets should snap together, sandwiching your natural lashes in between.\n    5.  **Adjust:** If needed, gently adjust the position of the lashes for a comfortable and secure fit.\n\n*   **Pros:**\n    *   No glue, so no mess or irritation from adhesives.\n    *   Reusable (if cleaned properly).\n    *   Relatively easy to apply once you get the hang of it.\n\n*   **Cons:**\n    *   Can feel a bit heavy or unnatural at first.\n    *   Can be tricky to align properly.\n    *   May not be as secure as glue-on lashes, especially in windy conditions.\n    *   The magnets can sometimes be visible.\n    *   Can be more expensive than traditional lashes and glue.\n\n**2. Self-Adhesive Eyelashes (with pre-applied adhesive):**\n\n*   **How they work:** These lashes come with a pre-applied adhesive strip on the band. You simply peel off the protective backing and apply them to your lash line. *However,* these still rely on adhesive, even if it's pre-applied. The adhesive may not be as strong as regular lash glue, and the lashes may not be as reusable.\n*   **Application:**\n    1.  **Prep lashes:** Curl your natural lashes and apply mascara.\n    2.  **Trim the lashes:** Measure the lashes against your lash line and trim any excess length from the *outer* corner.\n    3.  **Peel and Position:** Gently peel the lashes off the tray. Position the lash strip as close to your natural lash line as possible.\n    4.  **Secure:** Press the lash strip onto your lash line, starting from the inner corner and working your way outwards.\n*   **Pros:**\n    *   Less messy than glue.\n    *   Convenient for quick application.\n*   **Cons:**\n    *   The adhesive may not be very strong.\n    *   Reusability is limited, as the adhesive wears off quickly.\n    *   May cause irritation for some people.\n    *   Not truly \"glue-free,\" just pre-glued.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Hygiene:** Always clean your false eyelashes after each use to prevent bacterial buildup. Use a gentle makeup remover or cleanser to remove any residue.\n*   **Lash Line Health:** Be gentle when removing any type of false lashes to avoid damaging your natural lashes.\n*   **Patch Test:** Even with \"glue-free\" options, it's always a good idea to do a patch test on a small area of your skin before applying them to your entire lash line, especially if you have sensitive skin or allergies.  This is especially true for self-adhesive lashes.\n*   **Practice:** It takes practice to apply any type of false eyelashes correctly. Don't get discouraged if you don't get it right the first time.\n\n**In summary, magnetic lashes are the closest you'll get to truly \"glue-free\" false eyelashes. Self-adhesive lashes are simply pre-glued and may still cause similar reactions to regular lash glue.**\n",
